Since no surfactants and other hard templates were added during the whole preparation process, ethylene glycol with unique physicochemical properties and special molecular structure [24] could not only act as a solvent but also has the function of a soft template to facilitate the formation of Bi2MoO6 hollow microspheres during solvothermal synthesis [25,26]. In summary, based on above results, the formation mechanism of Bi2MoO6 hollow microspheres can be proposed as follows (Fig. 6
                        ): When Bi(NO3)3·5H2O and (NH4)6Mo7O24·4H2O were added to a mixed solvent system containing ethylene glycol, anhydrous ethanol and urea, the unstable Bi3+ and MoO6
                        6− ions combined to form amorphous solid microspheres with smooth surfaces and regular shapes via the action of ethylene glycol [27]. As the reaction proceeds, the remaining reactants and particles might adsorb and deposit on microsphere surfaces, and the large and small particles competed with each other for growth. On one hand, due to the complexation of ethylene glycol [28], the Bi2MoO6 microspheres might result in an inconsistent bulk density along the radial nanoparticles [24,26,27,29], and the bulk density of internal particles was low, which could be easily dissolved [26,27]. On the other hand, the crystallization of the microspheres was incomplete in a short solvothermal reaction time [30]. Due to the presence of position differences between the surface and interior of microspheres, the nanoparticles on microsphere surfaces crystallized quickly from amorphous shape to Bi2MoO6 crystal phase [14,25,31]. This preferential crystalline mode might make the internal amorphous structure particles dissolve easily [31]. Small molecule urea, which acts as a solubility regulator, can separate the interaction between macromolecules effectively, further increasing the dissolution rate of the nanoparticles [26,30,32]. Consequently, the voids were observed inside the microspheres, which gradually enlarged and finally formed a hollow structure. In addition, the NH3 decomposed by urea can guarantee the pH value of the whole system under the heating condition [26,30,32]. In this work, the decomposed OH− could provide a suitable alkaline environment for the formation of Bi2MoO6 hollow microspheres. The presence of the urea provided a favorable chemical environment for the whole hollowing process.
